Ambedkar called this the 'heart and soul' of the Constitution).\n\n**Note:** Right to Property was removed from Fundamental Rights in 1978 (44th Amendment) and is now a legal right under Article 300A."}
{"instruction": "How do I file an FIR in India?", "input": "", "output": "Filing an FIR (First Information Report) in India:\n\n**Step-by-step process:**\n\n1. **Go to the nearest Police Station** in whose jurisdiction the offence occurred.\n\n2. **Meet the Station House Officer (SHO)** or any police officer on duty.\n\n3. **Give your complaint** either orally or in writing. If oral, the police must reduce it to writing.\n\n4. **The officer will read it back** to you. You must sign or put your thumb impression after verifying it is correct.\n\n5. **Get a free copy of the FIR** — this is your legal right under Section 154(2) CrPC (now Section 173 BNSS).\n\n**If police refuse to file FIR:**\n- Send complaint by post to the Superintendent of Police (SP)\n- File a private complaint before a Magistrate under Section 156(3) CrPC\n- Approach the State Human Rights Commission\n\n**Online FIR:** Many states allow online FIR filing for minor offences at their state police websites.\n\n**Important:** An FIR can only be filed for cognizable offences (serious crimes where police can arrest without warrant). For non-cognizable offences, a complaint/NCR is filed.\n\nAlways consult a qualified advocate if you face difficulty filing an FIR."}
{"instruction": "What is anticipatory bail in India?", "input": "", "output": "**Anticipatory Bail** is a direction by the court to release a person on bail in anticipation of an arrest. It is granted under **Section 438 of CrPC** (now Section 482 of BNSS, 2023).\n\n**Key Features:**\n- Applied for BEFORE arrest (unlike regular bail which is after arrest)\n- Can be filed in the Sessions Court or High Court\n- Protects a person who has reason to believe they may be arrested for a non-bailable offence\n\n**Who can grant it:**\n- Sessions Court\n- High Court\n\n**Conditions usually imposed:**\n1. Person must be available for interrogation when required\n2. Must not tamper with evidence or influence witnesses\n3. Must surrender passport\n4. Must not leave the country without court permission\n\n**How to apply:**\n1. File an application through an advocate in Sessions Court\n2. State the grounds for apprehension of arrest\n3. Court will hear both sides\n4. If granted, person gets bail immediately upon arrest\n\n**Landmark case:** Gurbaksh Singh Sibbia vs State of Punjab (1980) - Supreme Court laid down guidelines for anticipatory bail.\n\nConsult a qualified criminal lawyer for filing anticipatory bail as the grounds must be clearly established."}
{"instruction": "What is the difference between IPC and BNS?", "input": "", "output": "**IPC (Indian Penal Code) vs BNS (Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita):**\n\nThe **Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023 (BNS)** replaced the Indian Penal Code, 1860 (IPC) with effect from **1 July 2024**.\n\n**Key Differences:**\n\n| Aspect | IPC (Old) | BNS (New) |\n|--------|-----------|----------|\n| Year | 1860 | 2023 |\n| Total Sections | 511 | 358 |\n| Effective from | 1862 | 1 July 2024 |\n| Origin | British era | Independent India |\n\n**Major Changes in BNS:**\n1. **Terrorism** defined and included as a specific offence (Section 113 BNS)\n2. **Organized Crime** now a separate offence (Section 111 BNS)\n3. **Sedition (Section 124A IPC)** removed; replaced by Section 152 BNS on acts endangering sovereignty\n4. **Community Service** introduced as a new form of punishment\n5. **Murder** - Section 302 IPC is now Section 101 BNS\n6. **Rape** - Section 376 IPC is now Section 63 BNS\n\nThe companion laws CrPC became BNSS and Indian Evidence Act became BSA simultaneously."}
{"instruction": "What are my rights if I am arrested in India?", "input": "", "output": "**Your Rights Upon Arrest in India (Constitutional & Legal Rights):**\n\n**1. Right to be informed of grounds of arrest (Article 22(1)):**\nPolice MUST tell you why you are being arrested. Failure to do so makes the arrest illegal.\n\n**2. Right to consult a lawyer (Article 22(1)):**\nYou have the right to consult and be defended by a lawyer of your choice immediately after arrest.\n\n**3. Right to free legal aid:**\nIf you cannot afford a lawyer, the State must provide one free of cost (Article 39A, Legal Services Authorities Act).\n\n**4. Right to be produced before Magistrate within 24 hours (Article 22(2)):**\nPolice cannot detain you for more than 24 hours without producing you before a Magistrate. This excludes travel time.\n\n**5. Right against self-incrimination (Article 20(3)):**\nYou cannot be forced to be a witness against yourself.\n\n**6. Right to inform family/friend:**\nUnder Section 50A CrPC (Section 47 BNSS), police must inform a family member or nominated person about your arrest.\n\n**7. Right against torture:**\nAny form of torture or custodial violence is illegal and punishable.\n\n**8. D.K. Basu Guidelines (Supreme Court):**\nPolice must follow strict guidelines including wearing name tags, preparing arrest memo, and allowing medical examination.\n\nIf any of these rights are violated, file a complaint with the Human Rights Commission or approach the High Court via habeas corpus petition."}
{"instruction": "What is the Right to Information (RTI) Act?", "input": "", "output": "**Right to Information Act, 2005 (RTI Act)**\n\nThe RTI Act empowers every Indian citizen to request information from any public authority. It promotes transparency and accountability in governance.\n\n**Key Provisions:**\n\n**Who can apply:** Any citizen of India.\n\n**What information can be sought:** Any information held by or under the control of a public authority including documents, records, memos, emails, opinions, etc.\n\n**How to file RTI:**\n1. Write application addressed to the Public Information Officer (PIO) of the concerned department\n2. Pay fee of Rs. 10 (Central Government) — BPL card holders are exempt\n3. Can be submitted in person, by post, or online at rtionline.gov.in\n4. Response must come within **30 days** (48 hours if life/liberty is involved)\n\n**If denied or unsatisfied:**\n- First Appeal to the First Appellate Authority within 30 days\n- Second Appeal to the Central/State Information Commission within 90 days\n\n**Exemptions (Section 8):** Information affecting national security, cabinet deliberations, personal privacy, and information given in fiduciary capacity are exempt.\n\n**Penalties:** PIO can be fined Rs. 250 per day up to Rs. 25,000 for delays or denial without reason.\n\nRTI is a powerful tool for citizens — use it to check status of applications, government schemes, and public works."}
{"instruction": "What is a PIL (Public Interest Litigation)?", "input": "", "output": "**Public Interest Litigation (PIL)**\n\nA PIL is a legal action filed in a court of law for the enforcement of public interest or general interest in which the public or a class of the community have pecuniary interest or some interest by which their legal rights or liabilities are affected.\n\n**Key Features:**\n- Can be filed by ANY citizen on behalf of the public\n- No direct personal interest required in the matter\n- Filed directly in High Court (Article 226) or Supreme Court (Article 32)\n- Filing fee is very nominal (often just Rs. 50)\n\n**Who can file:**\nAny citizen, NGO, journalist, or even a letter written to the Chief Justice can be treated as a PIL.\n\n**Common PIL subjects:**\n1. Environmental pollution\n2. Bonded labour and child labour\n3. Atrocities on women and minorities\n4. Non-payment of minimum wages\n5. Violation of fundamental rights\n6. Corruption in public offices\n\n**Landmark PILs in India:**\n- Vishaka vs State of Rajasthan (1997) - Sexual harassment at workplace guidelines\n- MC Mehta vs Union of India - Environmental protection\n- Hussainara Khatoon - Undertrial prisoners rights\n\n**How to file:**\n1. Draft a petition explaining the public issue\n2. Attach supporting evidence\n3. File in the High Court or Supreme Court Registry\n4. Court will issue notice to the respondent government/authority\n\nPIL is a unique Indian contribution to jurisprudence and a powerful tool for social change."}
{"instruction": "What are consumer rights in India?", "input": "", "output": "**Consumer Rights in India — Consumer Protection Act, 2019**\n\n**6 Basic Consumer Rights:**\n1. **Right to Safety** — Protection against hazardous goods and services\n2. **Right to Information** — Right to know quality, quantity, potency, price of goods\n3. **Right to Choose** — Access to variety of goods at competitive prices\n4. **Right to be Heard** — Consumer interests to be considered in policy making\n5. **Right to Redressal** — Right to seek redressal against unfair trade practices\n6. **Right to Consumer Education** — Right to acquire knowledge and skills\n\n**Where to file complaint:**\n\n| Claim Amount | Forum |\n|---|---|\n| Up to Rs. 50 lakhs | District Consumer Commission |\n| Rs. 50 lakhs to Rs. 2 crores | State Consumer Commission |\n| Above Rs. 2 crores | National Consumer Commission (NCDRC) |\n\n**How to file complaint:**\n1. Send legal notice to seller/company first\n2. File complaint on edaakhil.nic.in (online portal)\n3. Pay nominal court fee\n4. Complaint must be filed within 2 years of cause of action\n\n**Remedies available:**\n- Replacement of defective goods\n- Refund of price paid\n- Compensation for loss/injury\n- Removal of deficiency in service\n\nComplaints can be filed by the consumer themselves — no lawyer required for District Commission."}